\layout Title

On Differences of Zeta Values
\layout Author

Philippe Flajolet and Linas Vepstas
\layout Abstract

Finite differences of the Riemann zeta function at the integers are explored.
 Such quantities, which occur as coefficients in Newton series representations,
 have surfaced in works of Ma
\i \'{s}
lanka, Coffey, B
\i \'{a}
ez-Duarte, Voros and others.
 We apply the theory of N
\i \"{o}
rlund-Rice integrals in conjunction with the saddle point method or the
 residue theorem and derive precise asymptotic estimates.
 The method extends to Dirichlet 
\begin_inset Formula \( L\)
\end_inset 

-functions, in which case our estimates appear to be partly related to earlier
 investigations surrounding Li's criterion for the Riemann hypothesis. 
\layout Section

Introduction
\layout Standard

In recent times, a variety of authors have, for a variety of reasons, been
 led to considering properties of representations of the Riemann zeta function
 
\begin_inset Formula \( \zeta(s)=\sum 1/n^s\)
\end_inset 

 as a 
\emph on 
Newton interpolation series
\emph default 
.
 Amongst the many possible forms, we single out the one relative to a regularize
d
 version of Riemann zeta, namely, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation} \label{eq1}
\zeta(s)-\frac{1}{s-1}=\sum_{n=0}^\infty
(-1)^n b_n \binom{s}{n},
\end{equation}
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula \( \binom{s}{n}\)
\end_inset 

 is a binomial coefficient: 
\begin_inset Formula \[ 
\binom{s}{n}:=\frac{s(s-1)\cdots(s-n+1)}{n!}.
\]
\end_inset 

 Our results imply that the representation
\protected_separator 

\latex latex 

\backslash eqref{eq1}
\latex default 
 is valid thoughout the complex plane, its coefficients being given by a
 general formula in the calculus of finite differences
\protected_separator 

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Jordan65,Milne81,Norlund54}

\end_inset 

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation} \label{eq2}
b_n=
n(1-\gamma-H_{n-1})+\frac12+\sum_{k=2}^n \binom{n}{k}
(-1)^k\zeta(k),
\end{equation}
\end_inset 

 (Here, 
\begin_inset Formula \( H_n=1+\frac12+\cdots\frac1n\)
\end_inset 

 are the harmonic numbers.) Although the terms in the sum defining
\protected_separator 

\begin_inset Formula \( b_n\)
\end_inset 

 become exponentially large, the values of the 
\begin_inset Formula \( b_n\)
\end_inset 

 are exponentially small, 
\begin_inset Formula \[ 
b_n=\mathcal{O}\left(n^{1/4}e^{-2\sqrt{\pi n}}\right),
\]
\end_inset 

 while exhibiting a curious oscillatory behaviour.
 We shall prove (Theorem
\protected_separator 

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{zetacoeff-thm}

\end_inset 

) that, to the next leading order,
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[ 
b_n =2^{3/4}\pi^{-1/4}e^{-2\sqrt{\pi n}}\cos\left(2\sqrt{\pi n}+\frac{3\pi}{8}\right)n^{1/4}
+\mathcal{O}\left(n^{-1/4} e^{-2\sqrt{\pi n}}\right).
\]
\end_inset 


\layout Standard

