\layout Section

Newton series and zeta values
\layout Standard

This section defines the Newton series for the Riemann zeta that is to be
 studied, demonstrates some of its simple properties, and gives some generating
 functions for its coefficients.
 In this paper, a Newton series will be taken to be defined as
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation} \label{gennew}
\Phi(s)=\sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n c_n \binom{s}{n}.
\end{equation}
\end_inset 

 Given a function 
\begin_inset Formula \( \phi(s)\)
\end_inset 

, one may attempt to represent it in some region of the complex plane by
 means of such a series.
 Since the series 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Phi(s)\)
\end_inset 

 terminates at 
\begin_inset Formula \( s=0,1,2,\ldots\)
\end_inset 

, the conditions 
\begin_inset Formula \( \phi(m)=\Phi(m)\)
\end_inset 

 at the nonnegative integers imply that the candidate sequence 
\begin_inset Formula \( \{c_n\}\)
\end_inset 

 is linearly related to the sequence of values 
\begin_inset Formula \( \{\phi(m)\}\)
\end_inset 

 by 
\begin_inset Formula \[ 
\phi(m)=\sum_{n=0}^m (-1)^n c_n \binom{m}{n}.
\]
\end_inset 

 The triangular system can then be inverted to give (by the binomial transform
\protected_separator 

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{GrKnPa89}

\end_inset 

 or by direct elimination) 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation} \label{gencoeff}
c_n = \sum_{k=0}^{n} \binom{n}{k} (-1)^k \phi(k), \qquad n=0,1,2,\ldots\,.
\end{equation}
\end_inset 

 This choice of coefficients for
\protected_separator 

\latex latex 

\backslash eqref{gennew}
\latex default 
 determines the Newton series 
\emph on 
associated
\emph default 
 to 
\begin_inset Formula \( \phi\)
\end_inset 

.
 The coincidence of the function 
\begin_inset Formula \( \phi\)
\end_inset 

 and its associated series 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Phi\)
\end_inset 

 is, by construction, granted at least at all the nonnegative integers.
 The equivalence of 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Phi(m)=\phi(m)\)
\end_inset 

 can be extended to a region of the complex plane containing the integers,
 provided that the growth of the difference 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Phi(s)-\phi(s)\)
\end_inset 

 is bounded in the imaginary direction.
 This result is known as 
\emph on 
Carlson's theorem
\emph default 
, and is presented in a more precise form later in this paper.
\layout Standard

In the case of the Newton series for 
\begin_inset Formula \( \zeta(s)\)
\end_inset 

, the general relation
\protected_separator 

\latex latex 

\backslash eqref{gencoeff}
\latex default 
 provides the coefficients in the form 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation} \label{bn0}
b_n = s_0-ns_1+\sum_{k=2}^n \binom{n}{k} (-1)^k \left[\zeta(k)-\frac{1}{k-1}
\right],
\end{equation}
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation} \label{bn1}
s_0=\left[\zeta(s)-\frac{1}{s-1}\right]_{s=0}=\frac12,
\qquad
s_1=\lim_{s\rightarrow 1} \left[\zeta(s)-\frac{1}{s-1}\right] = \gamma.
\end{equation}
\end_inset 

 The harmonic numbers appear as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation} \label{bn2}
\sum_{k=2}^n \binom{n}{k}\frac{(-1)^k}{k-1}=1-n+nH_{n-1}.
\end{equation}
\end_inset 

 Equations 
\latex latex 

\backslash eqref{bn0}
\latex default 
, 
\latex latex 

\backslash eqref{bn1}
\latex default 
, 
\latex latex 

\backslash eqref{bn2}
\latex default 
 then entail that the 
\begin_inset Formula \( b_n\)
\end_inset 

, as defined by
\protected_separator 

\latex latex 

\backslash eqref{eq2}
\latex default 
, are indeed the coefficients of the Newton series associated to
\protected_separator 

\begin_inset Formula \( \zeta(s)-1/(s-1)\)
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard


\latex latex 

\backslash smallskip
\latex default 

\layout Standard

Before engaging in a detailed study of the
\protected_separator 

\begin_inset Formula \( b_n\)
\end_inset 

, we note a few simple facts regarding their elementary properties.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation} \label{deldef}
\delta_n:=\sum_{k=2}^n \binom{n}{k} (-1)^k \zeta(k),
\end{equation}
\end_inset 

 which are, up to minor adjustments, differences of zeta values at the integers.
 Defining the forward difference 
\begin_inset Formula \( \Delta f(x):=f(x+1)-f(x)\)
\end_inset 

, one has 
\begin_inset Formula \[ 
\delta_n= (-1)^n \Delta^n Z(x) \bigg|_{x=0},\]
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula \( Z(k)=\zeta(k)\)
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula \( k\geq2\)
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \( Z(0)=Z(1)=0\)
\end_inset 

.
 Expanding the zeta function according to its definition and exchanging
 the order of summations in the resulting double sum shows that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation} \label{simpdel}
\delta_n = \sum_{\ell\geq1} \left[\left(1-\frac{1}{\ell}\right)^n-1+\frac{n}{\ell}\right].
\end{equation}
\end_inset 

 It is surprising that such a simple sum should exhibit the complicated
 asymptotic behaviour described by Theorem
\protected_separator 

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{zetacoeff-thm}

\end_inset 

 below.
\layout Standard

The ordinary generating function for the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula \( \{\delta_n\}\)
\end_inset 

 is also of interest.
 Given the classical expansion
\protected_separator 

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{WhWa27}

\end_inset 

 of the logarithmic derivative 
\begin_inset Formula \( \psi(z)\)
\end_inset 

 of the Gamma function, 
\begin_inset Formula \[ 
\psi(1+z)+\gamma=\zeta(2)z-\zeta(3)z^2+\zeta(4)z^3-\cdots,
\]
\end_inset 

 one finds 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation} \label{delogf}
\sum_{n\geq2}\delta_n z^n =\frac{z}{(1-z)^2}\left[\psi\left(\frac{1}{1-z}\right)
+\gamma\right].
\end{equation}
\end_inset 

 The exponential generating function of 
\begin_inset Formula \( \delta_n\)
\end_inset 

 reflects
\protected_separator 

\latex latex 

\backslash eqref{simpdel}
\latex default 
 and is even simpler: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation} \label{delegf}
\sum_{n\geq2}\delta_n \frac{z^n}{n!}
=e^z\sum_{n\geq2} \zeta(n) \frac{(-z)^n}{n!}=e^z \sum_{\ell\geq1}
\left[e^{-z/\ell}-1+\frac{z}{\ell}\right]
.
\end{equation}
\end_inset 


